==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Fugue
<hw>Fugue</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., fr. It.
<ets>fuga</ets>, fr. L. <ets>fuga</ets> a fleeing, flight, akin to
<ets>fugere</ets> to fiee. See <er>Fugitive</er>.]</ety>
<fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A polyphonic composition, developed from a given
theme or themes, according to strict contrapuntal rules. The theme is
first given out by one voice or part, and then, while that pursues its
way, it is repeated by another at the interval of a fifth or fourth, and
so on, until all the parts have answered one by one, continuing their
several melodies and interweaving them in one complex progressive whole,
in which the theme is often lost and reappears.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All parts of the scheme are eternally chasing each other, like the
parts of a <qex>fugue</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. Taylor.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fuguist</ent>⟦br⟧
